          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Go Hobbit Farmer!  Chicago, IL  3/30/02<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.89)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813'>Andrew "Bee Boy" Sitte</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9813&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 31, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> I showed up at IIT for a 4-round LotR tournament, hoping to win 2 games with my Hobbit Farmer deck.  This was my second tournament; at the first, I went 2-3 with a modified starter deck.  Unfortunately, when we were ready to start, there were only 5 of us there.  Andrew Lanz ran off to find 3 other players so we could be sanctioned, and as they showed up they were introduced to the game and given decks to use.  Most of the guys played Star Trek, and were just getting in to LotR a little.  I realized I actually had a chance to win; only a couple other players looked very comptetitive, and only one of them was rare-heavy.  He also turned out to be a great player and opponent, the rares just make our game even tougher.  Heck, someone with lots of uncommons has an advantage over me :)<br>
<br>
I was using a deck based on Hobbit Farmer, with a total of 18 hobbit allies (17 playable; 2 Filiberts cuz he&#39;s so dang useful).  With Rosie, Gaffer, Farmer Maggot, 4 Party Guests, and Old Bilbo&#39;s Heir, I could heal 5 wounds a turn (or Bounders, Bilbo, whatever).  For shadow, I went with Moria Archery cuz I wanted to try it out, and it doesn&#39;t require many rares (I would have gone with normal Moria Swarm if I had more than 1 Armory).  Originally the deck had 6 rares, but last weekend I traded for a Swarms and Armory, and then on Thursday night I found a couple collectors trading 2 for 1, and added 3 Promises, rare Pippin, Mithril-coat, O Elbereth!, Goblin Domain, and one or two others.  The card that I most wanted to trade for (Thrors Map - I wanted 2 or 3 in the deck) I was unable to get; nobody I talked to had any extra.  Also, I own no There and Back Agains, a great card in a hobbit deck, and nobody brings them unless they&#39;re using them since it&#39;s common.<br>
<br>
I&#39;ll post a decklist soon (what I used, not what I wanted to use)<br>
<br>
Round 1 vs Andrew Lanz<br>
<br>
Andrew had only played a game or two before, but had most of the rules down.  He was using a modifier Aragorn FotR starter, so I figured I wouldn&#39;t have much trouble.  I decided I might as well go for site 9, even though my deck usually doesn&#39;t try.  I had a Hobbit Farmer right away, and played about 5 hobbits plus A Promise before moving.  He didn&#39;t play much, so I moved on to 3, took a couple of wounds, and let him go.  With Aragorn and Boromir both out, he was able to kill off the weak orcs that I threw down to draw cards as he marched to 3.  My turn, I used Master Proudfoot&#39;s ability twice and ended up playing 5 more Hobbits, another Promise, and 2 swords.  Lots of shadow also hit the discard, but with Intuition and some decent fighters I  made it to 4 unscathed.  There I moved on to 5, and he had no Balrog for me (I didn&#39;t have Filibert yet, but I had 1 Stealth and a Bounder for Merry to survive one).  He moved to site 4, where I laid down a bunch of archery, most of which was sucked up by Intimidates and then killed most of my minions, and stopped.  After playing O Elbereth (but no allies) I moved to 6, and after facing almost nothing, moved onto his 7.<br>
Boy, do I need Thror&#39;s Maps.  All of my allies went away.  Boo!  I lost all of my healers (Maggot, Gaffer, Rosy) there, plus 2 Bounders and 3 Farmers.  Thankfully, I survived the trip and drew a Bounder.<br>
His Legolas and Boromir died after facing a good deal of archery and skirmishes, but he made it to site 7.  I moved to his site 8, and he couldn&#39;t get 5 orcs out to stop me.  He did have 4 out though, Bounder was exerted, and I didn&#39;t have a single pumper for Frodo; if he played even 2 orcs at 9 Frodo would have died, so I stopped (His weakest on the table was an 8).  I was able to get 5 orcs out to stop him from moving on (not that he would have survived a double move) and with another promise, a healed Bounder, and an Intuition in hand, Frodo was safe up to 35.<br>
<br>
FW: 3(3)<br>
<br>
Props: Andrew, great job for a beginner<br>
Slops: Anduin Confluence.  Boo!!!<br>
<br>
Since we finished our game quickly, I helped 2 of the new players through their game so the TC could concentrate on his game.<br>
<br>
Round 2 vs Mark Coutre<br>
<br>
This was pretty much the battle for first place, and we both knew it.  Consequently, I remember more of it than my other games.  We sat next to each other the first game, and after he quickly overwhelmed his opponent he got to watch half of my game.  I had glanced over at his game once, and saw Arwen and Greenleaf, so was expecting quite a bit of trouble.  In order for my archery to be decently strong, I need to draw extrememly well, which I couldn&#39;t count on.  He started Gandalf, and I won the bid, but decided to make him go first (I also knew he was using Nazgul, and with as much pool as I potentially give out on my first turn, I&#39;d rather be moving to Buckelberry Ferry than Weatherhills or Weathertop.  Did I mention that I need Thror&#39;s Maps?  He started the Pony (dang, shoulda gone first) and gave Aragorn a Ranger Sword before coasting through to my site 3, Frodo&#39;s Bedroom.<br>
I laid down Proudfoot, who sent 3 shadow cards to my discard.  Boo!  Of course, then I drew and played a string of allies, 2 Promises, and a sword.  After moving to Buckleberry Ferry, there was 15 twilight on the table.  He played no Nazgul, but 2 Black Breaths.  YUCK!  That&#39;d screw my healing engine nicely, especially since I have no condition removal (the only tale in the deck is O E! G!, so rare Bilbo is better).  Anyway, with Filibert already out and 2 stealth cards, I decided to push on even with the 15 still there.   Twilight Witch-king, Twilight Spot-2-BorW, and Uliare Self-pumper came down after he played a Tip.  I ran Witch-king&#39;s first and lost (Pippin&#39;s head went flying).  He exerted to wound Frodo, so Twilight Spot-2-BorW could Spot 2 W, and was fierce along with Self-pumper.  Thankfully, the 2 stealths and Filibert were enough to cancel all 4 skirmishes before his Nazgul could even breathe on me.<br>
He pushed to 4 after playing Glamdring and removing 2.  I played Armory, then used up all of the pool playing They Are Coming, a Marksman, and a couple of Scavengers.  I didn&#39;t have any Runners left in my discard to TAC, or I would have played Goblin Domain too.<br>
I moved to 4, faced a strength 10 Sauron orc and Uliare Make-Nazgul-Fierce.  I dealt with them easily enough, Intuition/Filiber on the Nazgul (keeping the Breath/Tips in his support area as long as possible) and taking a wound from the orc.  He&#39;d only played 2 cards from hand, hadn&#39;t discarded on the reconcile, so if I moved to the bridge he&#39;d have had nearly 20 pool to work with, and with the haven coming up I didn&#39;t want to get Tips and Breaths so I stopped.<br>
His turn, he dropped a whole pile of stuff - Greenleaf (Why, oh Why didn&#39;t I played Goblin Domain the turn before?!) Saga/Tale, Aragorn&#39;s Bow, Elrond, Gandalf&#39;s Staff.  Out came a Marksman, a Bowman, a Runner, a Scavenger, and Flame of Udun.  Greenleaf shot down the Marksman, and Gandalf and Aragorn each took 2 wounds and Frodo a burden after a bunch of combat - er - skirmishing (I still play Middle Earth CCG lots, mix up my terms).  Thanks to a Servant of the Secret Fire, nothing was left on the table, and after my discard and draw, I had a Scavenger and 7 Free Peoples cards.  He made it to 6 with the Scavenger being shot down; I could have discarded 6 to play a couple of guys, but not lots, and it was pretty clear that I wasn&#39;t going to be able to harm him enough to stop Frodo so I decided to go for site 9.  I healed fully, used Proudfoot, played a few allies, my third Promise, and Mithril-coat before heading to the bridge, leaving him a hefty pile or 16 or so.  Luckily, he went for Balrog, and the Merry/Bounder team plus a Stealth left me in good shape.  I pushed on to 6, where Sam and Merry faced ofeasterlingainst a Nazgul each.  My heart racing, I played a Stealth to boost Sam to strength 11 to win his skirmish, and he didn&#39;t transfer Breath.  Whew.  Merry faced a fierce Nazgul, but we both passed on the first skirmish, and Merry used Filibert to cancel the second.  He meant to transfer the Breath/Tip on the first skirmish, and realized it then.<br>
He played Boromir, LoG, and moved to 7.  I threw down what I could, and used Bitter Hatred to kill Elrond (Legolas was 3 wounds from death thanks to Tale).  He ARV&#39;d my Commander, so there wasn&#39;t much out after combat, but he stopped.  I couldn&#39;t believe it.  That meant I could move once, to my 7, let him move to my 8 where I could spot 5 orcs, and then I could double move to victory.  Woot!  At 7, I faced Uliare Site-changer and Uliare Play-dead-minions.  Merry finally got a Tip and Breath, and with 3 wounds he&#39;d be gone right away next turn.  So, it was up to Sam and Frodo to make it.  Marks turn, he used Sleep, Caradhras, and moved to my site 8 - Brown Lands.  OH CRUD!  I forgot that I didn&#39;t have Shores of Nen Hithoel!  I was able to get out 2 Archer Troops, and a Bowman, and both Troops survived, while Boromir died.  He could have pushed on and made it with my hand, but he stopped.<br>
So, with just a few cards in my deck, I decided not to draw when I played an ally.  Stupid!  I forgot that I was double moving, it was the last turn...  Anyway, I used Bilbo to shuffle an Intuition in, but didn&#39;t draw it when I played my second ally.  I coulda used Proudfoot, but forgot.  I did have O Elbereth to play though, and hoped it would win me the game.  I moved to 8, facing Make-nazgul-fierce, Self-pumper, and Bill Ferny.  Sam was Tipped/Breathed by Self-pumper, needing Stealth and Bounder to not be overwhelmed by the fully pumped nazgul plus Bill.  Frodo faced Make-nazgul-fierce, and with his 10 strength, he wounded the wraith in both skirmishes and killed it.  I moved to 9 - He played another Fierce Nazgul, but with one Stealth in hand, 3 healthy Bounders, and Sam and Frodo at strength 9 and 10, it wasn&#39;t enough. <br>
<br>
FW: 3(6)<br>
<br>
Props: Mark, for a heck of a tight game<br>
       Elbereth, for being there to clinch it<br>
       Sam, cuz Promise rules and no burdens ain&#39;t shabby either<br>
Slops: Me, for not letting him go back and play a Tip/Breath at one point when he passed<br>
       Getting paired against the other 1st place contender 2nd round       <br>
<br>
Game 3 vs Brian<br>
Brian and I were the last undefeated players, but since he was just using a modified starter deck (Gandalf FotR) I thought it&#39;d be a piece of cake.  This game reminded me that my fellowship isn&#39;t very strong...<br>
I bid 4 to his 2 and went first, playing a Bounder, Guest, and Bilbo, plus 2 Swords and A Promise.  Pretty good, but no Farmer.  With Frodo and Merry both at 7 strength, getting to Rivendell against his Moria minions was easy.  He played Legolas for free with Gandalf, and proceeded to face one minion each on the move from 1 to 2 and 2 to 3, both of which died to Legolas during archery. <br>
Since I still had no Farmer and was at his Council Courtyard instead of my Frodo&#39;s Bedroom, I couldn&#39;t draw for the hobbit allies I played.  I could really use some Thror&#39;s Maps!  I played the 2 allies that I had, plus Mithril Coat and headed to his site 4 (Moria Lake I think).  He played a few orcs and They Are Coming.  I killed what I could and ran away from the rest, though Pippin may have taken a wound.  I moved again, to site 5, and didn&#39;t face too much opposition there either.  <br>
He added Gimli to his fellowship before moving to 4, where I played a few orcs and a Swarms, but didn&#39;t do much damage; only an Archer Troop survived.  He didn&#39;t want to get far behind, so he moved again, and Flame of Udun came out with a Marksman and Bowman.  Frodo washimmer by one arrow while Gimli and Legolas were exhausted by the other 3.  Frodo put on the ring to hide from the Bowman, Gandalf was wounded by the Troop, and Legolas used Defiance twice to kill the Marksman and survive long enough to help Gimli feed the Balrog.<br>
With Brian drawing mostly free people&#39;s cards, I thought I&#39;d have a free trip to site 7 after Sam made another Promise and Frodo prayed to Elbereth.  All of my allies were discarded, but I had only played 6 anyway (1 Farmer).  Of course, my allies all went away (foolish me), I only had one Intuition, and he set up Sam, Frodo, and Pippin to be overwhelmed.  Doh!  Sam died for the first time with that deck, and his Promises meant nothing.<br>
His Frodo and Gandalf weren&#39;t in good shape, but Boromir showed up to help them survive the trip to the haven (Sanctuary, that is).  He had 4 wounds on the 3 characters, but kept saying that he was going to die anyway, so he might as well press on.  He moved to site 7, where Boromir died after exhausting himself to keep Frodo alive.<br>
So, he was 2 sites from victory.  I was pretty sure that I could kill him, but I decided to see if I could double jump to 9.  I played a big string of allies (I finally hit the bulk of them) plus my 3rd (now worthless) Promise and moved to site 8.  Oh yeah - the Gandalf starter&#39;s site 8 is Shores, ain&#39;t it?  So, I knew he&#39;d be able to get out 5 orcs and stop me. He was able to get out 5, but it took dumping all but 1 card to They Are Coming.  I had 2 characters, so Frodo was facing 4 big orcs, and I have no PATHS in the deck.  He thought he&#39;d won - without Promises Frodo was just 7 strength, with Bounder he needed 21 to overwhelm, and with a Drums in the Deep he had 34.  I played a Stealth and and Intuition, so he needed 36 to overwhelm.  He growled, upset at discarding another Drums to TAC, but without doing that he wouldn&#39;t have had even 5 minions (the 4th minion was a TAC&#39;d Scavenger, the card he drew from Scimtar was the 5th minion).  I had another Intuition in hand anyway, so he really needed 45 to overwhelm.<br>
He moved to his site 8, and with 11 twilight I played 7 orcs to stop him.  I had enough in my hand to survive the move to 9 on my turn, but it never got that far - the 7 orcs were more than Gandalf and Frodo could handle.<br>
<br>
FW: 3(9)<br>
<br>
Props: Brian nearly overwhelmed me with a starter deck<br>
Slops: Sam, for making multiple Promises and then getting smeared<br>
       The Archery thing wasn&#39;t working, normal swarm with Shores is the way to go              <br>
<br>
Game 4 vs Bob<br>
I had already played both players with 7 points (Brian and Mark) so I paired down to face Bob, the TC.  He was using a Dwarf deck, which turned out to only have Frodo, Gimli, Farin, and a Dwarven Guard.  Four characters, low vitality...I figured it was time for my archery to shine.  I won the bid (of course - in all the games I&#39;ve played in the Chicago area, only once had my opponent bid over 3.  Average bid has been less than 2) and after playing a couple allies and a sword ran to 3.  I don&#39;t like to double move much, but I want to put the pressure on my opponents to double move to 3 so I don&#39;t have shadow choking my hand for two turns.  I faced a tracker and an Uruk.  The Uruk assigned itself to Sam, and used Ettenmoors to overwhelm after I Bounder&#39;d, so I had to Stealth.  I pressed on, and was able to keep the wounds at 5 (and one extra burden).<br>
He played a Dwarven Guard to start his turn.  Gimli got a Dwarven and Hand axe right away, and with Farin at 7 vs orcs, the scrubs I could play on his double jump ended up bloody on the plains.  I drew a Farmer during his turn, so dropped that, and after using Proudfoot once, ended up with the whole healing engine in place (only 2 Party Guests at the time though).  A Sword, a prayer, and A Promise, and they ran to site 4 (exert 2 or Gimli), facing 3 Sauron orcs (the first 2 were trackers).  I took one wound, which was easily erased the next turn.<br>
Bob played Thrarin, and moved to 4, facing a Bowman, Marksman, 2 Scavengers, and Scimtar&#39;d Runner.  He used &#39;Exert a Dwarf to wound 2 orcs&#39; but I ditched Armory to save the Marksman so everyone would have to face one.  The Dwarf Guard died, but Gimli won his skirmish and healed twice.  I stacked the winners on Swarms, but he moved again.  With the new Gimli, his fellowship of 3 gave me 7 twilight at the Bridge, plus one left over made 8.  Thank goodness I had a Host of Thousands so I could get a Runner to spot for Flame of Udun.  The Flame ate Thrarin, and then faced ofeasterlingainst Gimli.  Gimli was a 6, +3 from weapons, +8 from 2 Flurry of Blows, and +3 from something else, for a total of 20 against the Balrog.  Damage +3 ALMOST killed the Hog...that woulda been too cool.<br>
At that point I was pretty certain that I could crush him with my orcs, so I only moved once, having little trouble at 5.  He moved to site 6, where I got out 3 orcs, all at least 7 strength, so Farin died, leaving Frodo and Gimli alone.  With time running low, I almost moved twice, but I wasn&#39;t sure what site 7 he had.  Of course, if I had a Thror&#39;s Map, it wouldn&#39;t matter.<br>
His Frodo and Gimli, fully healed, moved to my site 7, where they both exerted, and faced a couple orcs; Frodo took a burden and Gimli killed his.  He moved again, to my Brown Lands.  I got out 7 archery, and 6 was enough to kill both of his companions.<br>
<br>
FW: 3(12)<br>
<br>
Props: Brown Lands finally did its job<br>
       Gimli for dealing 4 damage to the Balrog<br>
       Every hobbit survived for once!<br>
Slops: The Balrog, for having 5 vitality.  Loser.<br>
<br>
So, I won the tournament.  I took home a &#39;First Place Winner&#39; certificate and the rare foil is on its way.  There wasn&#39;t much to trade for there, but I did get a Servant of the Secret Fire.  Brian, who learned the game during round 1, ended up in second place after the tie-breaker with Mark, in 3rd.  Mark was the randomly-pulled common foil guy.<br>
<br>
